04183nam a22006855i 9780748626717DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222006stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486267177 a10.1515/97807486267172doi  a(DE-B1597)616337  a(OCoLC)1076783911  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a973.9132221 aPalmer, Niall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Twenties in America :bPolitics and History /cNiall Palmer. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBAAS Paperbacks : BAAS00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAckowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1 The Coming of Normalcy, 1920–1 -- t2 Normalcy in Practice, 1921–3 -- t3 Normalcy Abroad, 1921–3 -- t4 Coolidgean Normalcy, 1923–5 -- t5 High Tide of Normalcy, 1925–8 -- t6 Normalcy Looks Ahead, 1928–9 -- tConclusion: Looking Back at Normalcy -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis new, revisionist approach to the Twenties in America offers the first balanced account of the history and politics of this much-maligned decade.Focusing on the two Presidents of the 1920s, the book points out key distinctions between the governing styles and political philosophies of Warren Harding and Calvin Coolidge. It suggests Harding's executive style and achievements were not as poor as traditional portraits have claimed. Coolidge is presented in terms of his largely successful efforts to distance himself from the financial scandals associated with his predecessor and his encouragement of the major revival of much of the US economy.The author argues that the pace of social and technological change resulted in lines of conflict over poverty, race, religion and employment rights being redrawn as living standards rose, home and working conditions changed and old prejudices were challenged. Consequently, politicians found that old solutions became increasingly irrelevant to new realities.The narrative is placed in the familiar context of the Twenties: the motor car, jazz, F. Scott Fitzgerald, Hollywood, mass consumerism and the flapper.Key Features:The only balanced overview of the history and politics of America in the 1920sRevises the traditional views of the Presidencies of Harding and CoolidgePlaces the politics in its social and cultural context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnnées vingt (Vingtième siècle). 0aNineteen twenties. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074862037140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862671740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748626717423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748626717/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK